04251nam a22006495i 9780271075891DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20211997pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710758917 a10.1515/97802710758912doi  a(DE-B1597)583663  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBD241b.D85 1997 7aPHI0260002bisacsh04a121/.682201 aDunning, Stephen N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDialectical Readings :bThree Types of Interpretations /cStephen N. Dunning. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Paradigms of Science and Technology -- t2 Myths and Their Meanings -- t3 Frontiers in History -- t4 Variations on the Theme of Love -- t5 Dialectics of Identity -- t6 Interpreting Theories of Interpretation -- tConclusion -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aInterpretation pervades human thinking. Whether perception or experience, spoken word or written theory, whatever enters our consciousness must be interpreted in order to be understood. Every area of inquiry-art and literature, philosophy and religion, history and the social sciences, even many aspects of the natural sciences-involves countless opportunities to interpret the object of inquiry according to very different paradigms. These paradigms may derive from the language we speak, the nature of our education, or personal preferences. The abundance and diversity of paradigms make interpretation both fascinating in its complexity and often frustrating for the conflicts it generates. In Dialectical Readings, Dunning distinguishes three types of interpretation, each defined in terms of a distinctive dialectical way of thinking: theoretical interpretation, which assumes binary oppositions; transactional interpretation, which seeks reciprocal relations; and transformational interpretation, which discerns paradoxical meanings. Dunning offers new and insightful readings of familiar texts by B. F. Skinner, Claude Lévi-Strauss, Lee Benson, Roland Barthes, Friedrich Nietzsche, and Michel Foucault and sheds new light on works by Thomas Kuhn, Joseph Campbell, Reinhold Niebuhr, Søren Kierkegaard, Paul Tillich, and Paul Ricoeur. Dialectical Readings enables readers to recognize diverse dialectical approaches to understanding-their own as well as those of others-in a way that provides new and helpful insights into a wide variety of subjects in which conflicting interpretations abound.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aDialectic. 0aHermeneutics. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271075891zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271075891423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271075891.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK